            . I live in <placeName id="t18280221-223-crimeloc1186">Edgeware-road</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18280221-223-crimeloc1186" type="placeName" value="Edgeware-road"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18280221-223-crimeloc1186" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280221-223-off1184 t18280221-223-crimeloc1186"></join>, and am a haberdasher. On the evening of the 17th of January, about 7 o'clock, two boys alarmed me - I missed a piece of handkerchiefs off a bar, four feet inside the shop; they were safe five minutes before: Charles Barker is <rs id="t18280221-223-viclabel1187" type="occupation">owner of the shop</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280221-223-victim1300 t18280221-223-viclabel1187"></join> - I had been into the kitchen.</p>
               <p>Prisoner AYLESWORTH. Q. Did you not say at the office, that you took Wilkie into your shop? A. I went out and brought a lad in, who I thought was Wilkie; and while I fetched a boy to recognize him he was gone.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280221-223-person1302">
                  EDMOND 
                  IMBER
               <interp inst="t18280221-223-person1302" type="surname" value="IMBER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-223-person1302" type="given" value="EDMOND"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-223-person1302" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I know the prisoners by seeing them several times about the Edgeware-road; on the evening of Thursday, on the 17th of January, I saw Wilkie come up to Mr. Barker's door, and go in on his hands and knees - Aylesworth was standing at the window; Wilkie snatched down a length of something - I could not see what; he came out and they ran away - I alarmed the people in the shop, and saw the prisoners at the office on the Saturday.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280221-223-person1303">
                  HENRY 
                  LANGLEY
               <interp inst="t18280221-223-person1303" type="surname" value="LANGLEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-223-person1303" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-223-person1303" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I know the prisoners. On the 17th of January, between seven and eight o'clock in the evening, I saw them standing at Barker's door - Aylesworth stood at the window; Wilkie went into the shop on his hands and knees, and pulled down a long length of something - they ran away; I am certain they are the boys.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280221-223-person1304">
                  PHILIP 
                  WEBSTER
               <interp inst="t18280221-223-person1304" type="surname" value="WEBSTER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-223-person1304" type="given" value="PHILIP"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-223-person1304" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I received a description, and took the prisoners on the 19th, but found no goods on them.</p>
